{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584097"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:37:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:37:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14394"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14394"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.35,0.09,0.11,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57281"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7089"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14394"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42740"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4901"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6835"},{"type":"tags","id":"7213"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16909"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17121"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17814"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57281"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe phrenic nerve is an important structure in the neck that provides motor innervation to the diaphragm. It originates from the cervical spinal nerves C3-C5 and descends through the neck before entering the thorax.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscle groups does the phrenic nerve pass anterior to as it enters the thorax?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Scalene muscles","Sternocleidomastoid muscles","Omohyoid muscles","Infrahyoid muscles","Platysma muscle"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe phrenic nerve originates from the cervical spinal nerves C3-C5 and descends through the neck. As it enters the thorax, the phrenic nerve passes anterior to the \u003Cstrong\u003Escalene muscles\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically the anterior scalene muscle, as it enters the thorax. This anatomical relationship is important for understanding the nerve\u0027s pathway and potential sites of injury or compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esternocleidomastoid muscles\u003C/strong\u003E are located more superficially and laterally in the neck, and the phrenic nerve does not typically pass anterior to them. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eomohyoid muscles\u003C/strong\u003E are thin, ribbon-like muscles in the neck that do not have a direct relationship with the phrenic nerve\u0027s path. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einfrahyoid muscles\u003C/strong\u003E are a group of four paired muscles in the anterior neck, but the phrenic nerve does not pass anterior to them. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eplatysma muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is a superficial muscle of the neck and does not have a direct relationship with the phrenic nerve\u0027s path.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the anatomical relationships of the phrenic nerve is crucial for medical procedures in the neck region and for diagnosing conditions that may affect diaphragmatic function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The phrenic nerve enters the thorax anterior to the anterior scalene muscle.","The phrenic nerve originates from cervical spinal nerves C3-C5 and descends through the neck to innervate the diaphragm."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Auchincloss HG, Donahue DM. Prevention and Management of Nerve Injuries in Thoracic Surgery. Thorac Surg Clin. 2015 Nov;25(4):509-15. doi: 10.1016/j.thorsurg.2015.07.012. PMID: 26515950."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42740"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14394"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42740"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T18:30:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T18:58:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7089"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57281"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"desc